It's often the case where the labels of an axis doesn't properly fit as we show above. In that case a solution is to rotate them.

In[17]:

We can include both the total bil and the tip on the same figure

In[30]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.bar(bill_per_day.index, bill_per_day['total_bill'])

ax.set_xlabel('Days')
ax.set_ylabel('Amount ($)')
Out[30]:

However, the above is incomplete withoug a legend. Let's do that

In[31]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

ax.bar(bill_per_day.index, bill_per_day['tip'], bottom=bill_per_day['total_bill'], label='Tip ($)')

            xytext=(48,1),arrowprops={})

String form:    AxesImage(shape=(4, 4))
File:           ~/anaconda3/lib/python3.11/site-packages/matplotlib/image.py
Docstring:     
An image attached to an Axes.

Parameters
----------
ax : `~matplotlib.axes.Axes`
    The axes the image will belong to.
cmap : str or `~matplotlib.colors.Colormap`, default: :rc:`image.cmap`
    The Colormap instance or registered colormap name used to map scalar
    data to colors.
norm : str or `~matplotlib.colors.Normalize`
    Maps luminance to 0-1.
interpolation : str, default: :rc:`image.interpolation`
    Supported values are 'none', 'antialiased', 'nearest', 'bilinear',
    'bicubic', 'spline16', 'spline36', 'hanning', 'hamming', 'hermite',
    'kaiser', 'quadric', 'catrom', 'gaussian', 'bessel', 'mitchell',
    'sinc', 'lanczos', 'blackman'.
interpolation_stage : {'data', 'rgba'}, default: 'data'
    If 'data', interpolation
    is carried out on the data provided by the user.  If 'rgba', the
    interpolation is carried out after the colormapping has been
    applied (visual interpolation).
origin : {'upper', 'lower'}, default: :rc:`image.origin`
    Place the [0, 0] index of the array in the upper left or lower left
    corner of the axes. The convention 'upper' is typically used for
    matrices and images.
extent : tuple, optional
    The data axes (left, right, bottom, top) for making image plots
    registered with data plots.  Default is to label the pixel
    centers with the zero-based row and column indices.
filternorm : bool, default: True
    A parameter for the antigrain image resize filter
    (see the antigrain documentation).
    If filternorm is set, the filter normalizes integer values and corrects
    the rounding errors. It doesn't do anything with the source floating
    point values, it corrects only integers according to the rule of 1.0
    which means that any sum of pixel weights must be equal to 1.0. So,
    the filter function must produce a graph of the proper shape.
filterrad : float > 0, default: 4
    The filter radius for filters that have a radius parameter, i.e. when
    interpolation is one of: 'sinc', 'lanczos' or 'blackman'.
resample : bool, default: False
    When True, use a full resampling method. When False, only resample when
    the output image is larger than the input image.
**kwargs : `~matplotlib.artist.Artist` properties
Init docstring:
Parameters
----------
norm : `.Normalize` (or subclass thereof) or str or None
    The normalizing object which scales data, typically into the
    interval ``[0, 1]``.
    If a `str`, a `.Normalize` subclass is dynamically generated based
    on the scale with the corresponding name.
    If *None*, *norm* defaults to a *colors.Normalize* object which
    initializes its scaling based on the first data processed.
cmap : str or `~matplotlib.colors.Colormap`
    The colormap used to map normalized data values to RGBA colors.

ax.set_ylabel('Petal length')

fig.set_size_inches([10,5])

Saving a figure

In[61]:
plt.style.use('ggplot')
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.boxplot([setosa_petal_length, virginica_petal_length, versicolor_petal_length])
ax.set_xticklabels(['Setosa','Virginica', 'Versicolor'])
ax.set_xlabel('Species')
ax.set_ylabel('Petal length')

fig.savefig('iris_boxplot.pdf')
fig.savefig('iris_boxplot.png', dpi=300)

Exercise 1

We will work with the diamonds dataset. The dataset is available through the seaborn package. You will have to run the following: diamonds = sns.load_dataset('diamonds'). For all the plots use a customed style of your choice.

  • Create a scatter plot with the carat on the x axis and the price variable on the y axis. Label the axis appropriately.
  • Create the same scatter plot as above, but this type use a different colour for each cut value. Label the axis appropriately and include a legend.
  • Create a bar chart showing the price for the different colours. Add also standard error bars. Add also standard error bars. To calculate the standard error of the mean you can use the scipy.stats.sem.
  • Create a stacked bar chart including the mean values of the x, y and z columns for each clarity value.
  • Create a boxplot with the price range for the different cut values.
  • Calculate the Pearson correlations amongst all numeric columns. Create a heatmap plot from the correlation matrix, including a colour bar showing the range of colours for the corresponding correlation values.

Exercise 2

We will work with the snp_variants.txt dataset. For all the plots use a customed style of your choice.

  • Create a horizontal bar chart with the number of SNP variants of each chromosome.
  • Create separate line plots for each chromosome depicting the base composition of the Reference column along non-overlapping windows of 10,000,000 base pairs (you will need to estimate first the frequency of each base [A,G,C,T] for every ten million base pairs). Save the plot in a pdf format.
  • In the case of the first chromosome include annotation text. In particular add to the plot the text Position of interest at a suitable location and point using an arrow to the location where the frequency of the G base starts declining.
